@page
@model IndexModel
@{
    ViewData["Title"] = "Home page";
}

<div class="text-center">
    <h1 class="display-4">Welcome</h1>
    <p>Learn about <a href="https://learn.microsoft.com/aspnet/core">building Web apps with ASP.NET Core</a>.</p>
</div>

<center>
    <br>
    <div class="pstyling">Scrum Teams are the fundamental, self-managing unit of the Scrum framework,
        designed to deliver valuable product increments in short iiterative cycles called Sprints. <br>
        Typically consisting of 10 or fewer people, these teams are cross-functional, meaning they posses 
        all the skills necessary to create value without relying on external members.<br><br>
        Here is an overview of Scrum teams based on the 2020 Scrum Guide and industry best practices:</div><br>
    
    <div class="row">
        <div class="column"><h3>1. Core Accountabilities</h3>
            <div class="pstyling">Scrum defines three key roles within the team:<br>
            <b>Developers:</b> Committed to creating a usable, high-quality increment each Sprint.<br>
            <b>Product Owner (PO):</b> Maximizes product value by managing the Product Backlog and prioritizing work.<br>
            <b>Scrum Master:</b> Establishes Scrum, coaches the team, and removes impediments.<br></div>
        </div>
    
        <div class="column"> <h3>2. Key Characteristics & Operation</h3>
            <div class="pstyling"><b>Self-Managing & Cross-Functional:</b> The team decides how to work and possesses all 
            necessary skills to deliver, typically with 10 or fewer members.<br>
            <b>Focused:</b> Dedicated to a single product and goal.<br>
            <b>Events & Artifacts:</b> Operates in Sprints, using Sprint Planning, Daily Scrum, Review, and 
            Retrospective to manage the Product Backlog, Sprint Backlog, and Increment.<br></div>
        </div>
    
        <div class="column"><h3>3. High-Performing Teams & Challenges</h3>
            <div class="pstyling">Effective teams demonstrate shared <b>ownership</b>, high psychological safety, and frequent, <b>valuable</b>
            releases. <br>Common pitfalls include <b>"Waterscrumfall"</b> (waterfall in disguise), lack of a clear 
            <b>Sprint Goal</b>, and low empowerment.</div>
        </div>
    </div>
    </center>
    
